s apt, for the following reasons:
=C2=A0
(1) The word "tu" indicates some i=
rony or contrast. If you say "He rules the bridge of dharma. Then again, he=
 destroys the path of adharma", there is no such contrast. Basically, I see=
 "tu" as a misfit there.
(2) Bhairava is not necessarily a deity destroying=
 adharma. In fact, he stands more for liberation and for destroying the dis=
tinction in one's mind between dharma and adharma. For example, he is depic=
ted as roaming around naked drinking wine.
=C2=A0
BTW, observe the imagery.=
 Line before says "dharma setu pAlakaM" - the ruler of the bridge of dharma=
. Dharma is merely seen as a bridge here. Bridge to what? Obviously bridge =
over the sea of samsara and into infinite freedom. Bhairava not only contro=
ls the bridge, but his main purpose is to take one into infinite freedom fr=
om that bridge. Thus, swadharma mArga nAshakaM fits nicely following that l=
ine.
=C2=A0
BTW, some people may be tempted to worship and Bhairava and emu=
late him by drinking wine or roaming naked in a smashan. That may not neces=
sarily liberate one. Please note that Bhairava is not free becausehe drinks=
 wine and roams naked. He is already free and does those things becausehe i=
s free. In any case, even Bhairava, the deity of destroying right-wrong dis=
tinctions in mind and ringing in liberation is described as "dharma setu pa=
laka"! Dharma is very important. Until you reach the shore of infinite free=
dom, you HAVE to stay afloat of the ocean ofsamsara, by getting atop the br=
idge of dharma! Otherwise you will sink in the ocean of samara, toppled by =
the waves of delusion. Though one needs to jump off the bridge in the end, =
"the end" is not anywhere near for most people on earth and they better rea=
lize it!

